According to a report released earlier this year from The Pew Charitable Trusts' Economic Mobility Project, one in three American families experienced unemployment at some point between 1999 and 2009. The report, "Hard Choices: Navigating the Economic Shock of Unemployment," says families without savings and assets that they can turn to during emergencies are vulnerable to inflicting long-term damage on their finances. Indeed, unemployment can lead to an emptying out of retirement and college savings accounts, as well as the loss of other assets, like a home.
